The Japanese authorities last year deported a record  70,404 people, according to an official report released Sunday.
Deportations for violating immigration laws rose 3.8 percent from 1992. It  was the first time the number has topped 70,000, said the report by the  justice ministry which controls immigration offices.
Illegal workers accounted for 64,341 of the total, rising 3.5 percent from  the previous year, it said.
Thais topped the list of illegal workers, accounting for 20 percent,  followed by Malaysians with 19 percent, South Koreans with 18 percent and  Iranians with 14 percent, the report said.
The ministry said that the number of foreigners who were denied entry into  Japan last year went down 26.4 percent from 1992 to 18,960.
